# Project: Wellness Shop (built on next-commerce-community template)

## What this is
A personal health & wellness e-commerce store (skincare, supplements, personal
care), ~50 products. Built on the `next-commerce-community` template. The goal
is to keep the template's UI/UX and add REAL Stripe payments (card, Apple Pay,
Google Pay) where the template currently only has a fake payment UI.

## Stack (already in the template ŌĆö do not replace)
- Next.js 16 (App Router) + React 19 + TypeScript
- Redux Toolkit for cart state (`src/redux/features/cart-slice.ts`)
- Tailwind CSS
- Products currently in `src/components/Shop/shopData.ts` (static array, NOT
  Sanity yet ŌĆö Sanity packages are installed but unused; keep it this way unless
  the user explicitly asks to move to Sanity)
- next-auth (login), nodemailer (email) ŌĆö already present

## What we are ADDING (the main task)
Real Stripe payment processing:
- `src/lib/stripe.ts` ŌĆö Stripe server client
- `src/app/api/checkout/route.ts` ŌĆö creates a Stripe PaymentIntent
- `src/app/api/webhook/route.ts` ŌĆö receives payment confirmation
- `src/components/Checkout/StripePayment.tsx` ŌĆö Stripe Payment Element
  (this is where Apple Pay / Google Pay render automatically)
- Wire these into existing `PaymentMethod.tsx` and `Checkout/index.tsx`

## Key facts about the existing code
- Cart items shape (from cart-slice.ts):
  `{ id: number, title: string, price: number, discountedPrice: number,
     quantity: number, imgs?: {...} }`
- Cart total comes from `selectTotalPrice` = sum of `discountedPrice * quantity`
- `selectCartItems` / `selectTotalPrice` selectors live in cart-slice.ts
- Product source of truth for prices: `src/components/Shop/shopData.ts`
- The checkout `<form>` in `Checkout/index.tsx` currently has NO submit handler
- `PaymentMethod.tsx` is currently just radio buttons (bank/cash/paypal) with
  no real processing

## Critical rules ŌĆö do not break these
1. **Never trust prices from the client / Redux.** The checkout API route MUST
   recalculate the order total server-side by looking up each item's
   `discountedPrice` in `shopData.ts` using the item `id`. The client only sends
   `[{ id, quantity }]`.
2. **Currency: AED.** Stripe amounts are in fils ŌĆö multiply by 100 and
   Math.round. (Template demo prices look like USD; when the user adds real
   products, treat the numbers as AED.)
3. **Payment Element handles Apple Pay / Google Pay automatically** via
   `automatic_payment_methods: { enabled: true }`. Do NOT build custom wallet
   buttons.
4. **Apple Pay only renders on HTTPS + Safari/iOS** ŌĆö never on localhost. This
   is expected; don't try to "fix" it. Test wallets on the deployed Vercel URL.
5. The webhook route must read the **raw body** with `req.text()` (never
   `req.json()`) so Stripe signature verification works.
6. Keep the template's existing components, styling, and Redux structure intact.
   Add payment as a new layer; don't rewrite cart or product logic.

## Conventions
- Use the `@/` import alias (maps to `src/`).
- `"use client"` only where needed (payment form, anything with hooks/state).
- New API routes go under `src/app/api/`.

## Env vars (never commit real values; put in .env.local)
- NEXT_PUBLIC_STRIPE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY
- STRIPE_SECRET_KEY
- STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET

## Tasks the user may do next
- Replace demo electronics in `shopData.ts` with real wellness products
- Replace product images in `public/images/products/`
- Add order persistence + email confirmation (nodemailer is already installed)
- Optionally migrate products to Sanity later

## When unsure
Keep it simple and cheap to run (~50 products, personal shop). Ask before large
architectural changes (e.g. moving to Sanity, adding a database). Explain the
plan before writing significant code.